f memory that were developed in classical antiquity and adapted to the specific circumstances of his own time. Julia Dominguez explores the many spaces that memory created for itself in early modern Spain, particularly in the fields of philosophy, medicine, rhetoric, mnemotechnics, the visual arts, and pedagogy. Engaging with primary and archival sources, Quixotic Memories provides a new reading of Cervantes’ famous novel by tracing the socio-historical and cultural prominence of memory throughout the author’s lifetime.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aMemory in literature. 0aMemoryxSocial aspectszSpainxHistory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Spanish & Portuguese.2bisacsh  aCervantine.  aDon Quixote.  aMiguel de Cervantes.  aRenaissance literature.  aSancho.  aSpanish literature.  aart of memory.  aearly modern Spain.  aearly modern literature.  amemory.  amnemonic.  amnemotechnics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076715540uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148754391440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487543914423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487543914/original  a978-3-11-076715-5  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK